│ THOUGHT: Now I can see the exact location of the problem. The issue is in   │
│ the `DecrUnsched` lambda at line 5403-5404. The condition `(IsControl ||    │
│ Data->hasValidDependencies())` is supposed to prevent calling               │
│ `incrementUnscheduledDeps` when dependencies are invalid, but there's a     │
│ logical flaw here.                                                          │
│                                                                             │
│ The problem is that when `IsControl` is true, we skip the                   │
│ `hasValidDependencies()` check, but we still call                           │
│ `incrementUnscheduledDeps(-1)`. However, if the ScheduleData doesn't have   │
│ valid dependencies (i.e., `Dependencies == InvalidDeps`), then calling      │
│ `incrementUnscheduledDeps` will trigger the assertion failure.              │
│                                                                             │
│ The fix is to ensure that we only call `incrementUnscheduledDeps` when the  │
│ ScheduleData actually has valid dependencies, regardless of whether it's a  │
│ control dependency or not. Control dependencies should also have valid      │
│ dependencies initialized before being scheduled.                            │
│                                                                             │
│ Looking at the code more carefully, I think the issue is that control       │
│ dependencies might not have their dependencies properly initialized. The    │
│ proper fix is to modify the condition to always check                       │
│ `hasValidDependencies()` before calling `incrementUnscheduledDeps`.         │
│                                                                             │
│ ```bash                                                                     │
│ sed -i '5403s/if ((IsControl || Data->hasValidDependencies()) &&/if         │
│ (Data->hasValidDependencies() &&/'                                          │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                             │
│ ```                                                                         │
